            <th>Age Group</th>
            <th>Starting Dose</th>
            <th>Maximum Dose</th>
            <th>Timing</th>
            <th>Format Recommendation</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Under 3 years</strong></td>
            <td>Not recommended</td>
            <td>Pediatrician only</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Liquid drops if prescribed</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Ages 3-5</strong></td>
            <td>0.5mg</td>
            <td>1mg</td>
            <td>30-60 min before bed</td>
            <td>Liquid drops or low-dose gummy</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Ages 6-8</strong></td>
            <td>0.5-1mg</td>
            <td>3mg</td>
            <td>30-60 min before bed</td>
            <td>Low-dose children's gummy</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Ages 9-12</strong></td>
            <td>1mg</td>
            <td>3-5mg</td>
            <td>30-60 min before bed</td>
            <td>Children's gummy</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Teens 13+</strong></td>
            <td>1-2mg</td>
            <td>5mg</td>
            <td>30-60 min before bed</td>
            <td>Teen or adult low-dose gummy</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Less is more with melatonin for children.</strong> A 2022 JAMA Pediatrics study found that 0.5mg melatonin was equally effective as 3mg for reducing sleep-onset latency in children ages 6-12. Higher doses did not produce faster or better sleep but did increase the risk of next-morning grogginess and vivid dreams. Always start at the lowest dose and increase only under pediatrician guidance.</p>
    </div>

