    <p>Zarbee's is founded by a pediatrician and formulated specifically for children. The brand's reputation for clean ingredients and pediatric focus provides an extra layer of confidence for parents. The honey-sweetened formula avoids artificial sweeteners, and the 1mg dose aligns with pediatric dosing guidelines. For more sleep gummy options for all ages, see our <a href="/best-melatonin-gummies/">best melatonin gummies</a> and <a href="/best-sleep-gummies/">best sleep gummies</a> guides.</p>

    <!-- THE JAMA DOSING ACCURACY PROBLEM -->
    <h2>The Dosing Accuracy Problem: Why It Matters for Kids</h2>

    <p>A 2023 JAMA study tested 25 melatonin gummy products marketed for children and found alarming results:</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>74% to 347% of Label</h4>
        <p>Actual melatonin content in tested products ranged from 74% to 347% of the stated dose. One product labeled as 1mg actually contained 3.47mg — over three times the intended amount for a child.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Only 3 of 25 Were Accurate</h4>
        <p>Just 12% of tested products had melatonin content within 10% of the labeled amount. The remaining 88% were either significantly over- or under-dosed. This is a systemic quality control issue in the supplement industry.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Choose verified products for children.</strong> Given the dose accuracy concerns, we strongly recommend selecting children's melatonin products with USP Verification, NSF International certification, or a published Certificate of Analysis (CoA) from an independent lab. Children's lower body weight makes them more sensitive to dose variations — a product containing 347% of labeled melatonin in an adult is inconvenient; in a 40-pound child, it could cause significant next-day drowsiness and disrupted sleep architecture.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SAFETY CONSIDERATIONS -->
    <h2>Safety Considerations for Parents</h2>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="lock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Storage Safety</h4>
        <p>Melatonin gummies look and taste like candy. Store in a child-proof container in a high cabinet. Poison Control received over 260,000 pediatric melatonin exposure calls between 2012 and 2021 — a 530% increase driven largely by gummy format accessibility.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Duration of Use</h4>
        <p>Use melatonin as a short-term aid (1-3 months maximum) while establishing sleep hygiene habits. Schedule periodic "melatonin holidays" — 1-2 weeks off every 2-3 months — to assess whether your child still needs it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="baby" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Age Appropriateness</h4>
        <p>Gummies pose a choking risk for children under 4. For toddlers, use liquid melatonin drops if recommended by a pediatrician. Never give adult melatonin products (typically 5-10mg) to children.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Underlying Conditions</h4>
        <p>Persistent sleep difficulties in children may indicate underlying conditions — sleep apnea, anxiety, ADHD, or restless leg syndrome. If melatonin does not resolve sleep issues within 2-4 weeks, seek a pediatric sleep evaluation rather than increasing the dose.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- VERDICT -->
    <div class="verdict">
      <h3>The Bottom Line for Parents</h3>
      <p><strong>Start with sleep hygiene, not melatonin.</strong> Consistent bedtime routines, screen elimination, and dark sleeping environments resolve the majority of pediatric sleep difficulties without any supplementation.</p>
      <p><strong>If melatonin is appropriate, use the lowest dose.</strong> Start at 0.5mg for children under 6, 1mg for ages 6-12. Research shows lower doses are equally effective with fewer side effects. Give it 30-60 minutes before the desired bedtime.</p>
      <p><strong>Choose verified products.</strong> Given the documented dose accuracy problems (74-347% of label claims), select only products with USP, NSF, or independent CoA verification. Your child deserves the confidence that the labeled dose matches the actual dose.</p>
      <p><strong>Consult your pediatrician.</strong> Melatonin is an over-the-counter supplement, but it should be treated as a medication decision for children. Your pediatrician can rule out underlying conditions, recommend age-appropriate dosing, and monitor for side effects.</p>
    </div>

