      <details class="fq"><summary>Can kids take melatonin every night?</summary><p>Short-term nightly use (up to 3 months) is generally safe. However, experts recommend periodic "melatonin holidays" to reassess need. Melatonin should support habit formation, not replace good sleep hygiene permanently.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What are melatonin side effects in children?</summary><p>Morning drowsiness (usually from too high a dose), headaches, increased bedwetting, vivid dreams, dizziness, and mild stomach discomfort. Side effects are dose-dependent and resolve when the dose is reduced.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does melatonin affect puberty?</summary><p>No clinical evidence links melatonin supplementation to delayed or accelerated puberty in children at standard doses. However, long-term data is limited, which is why pediatricians recommend limiting duration of use.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Why do children's melatonin gummies have inaccurate doses?</summary><p>A 2023 JAMA study found 88% of tested products were inaccurate (74-347% of label). This is because melatonin is a supplement, not a drug, and manufacturing standards are less stringent. Choose USP or NSF-certified products.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What should parents try before melatonin?</summary><p>Consistent bedtime routine, screen elimination 60+ minutes before bed, dark room with blackout curtains, cool temperature (65-68°F), daily exercise, no caffeine, and consistent wake times. These resolve sleep issues in 60-70% of children.</p></details>
